[
    {
        "content": "<p>What can we do to make the <code>abel</code> tactic work in <code>Addcircle 1</code>, such that the tactic is aware that <code>((1 / 2 : ℝ) : AddCircle 1) = ((3 / 2 : ℝ) : AddCircle 1)</code>?</p>\n<p><code>abel</code> and <code>ring</code> support natural, integer and rational numbers. The problem with the rational numbers is that it want to represents <code>1 / 2</code> using division in <code>AddCircle 1</code>, which doesn't exist.</p>",
        "id": 520218983,
        "sender_full_name": "Jovan Gerbscheid",
        "timestamp": 1748110290
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If you can move this to a relation on <code>Real</code> (e.g., <code>PMOD</code>), then it should be easy to write a <code>norm_num</code> extension.</p>",
        "id": 520221353,
        "sender_full_name": "Yury G. Kudryashov",
        "timestamp": 1748112231
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It had not occured to me that norm_num can be taught about the PMOD relation</p>",
        "id": 520221484,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1748112326
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Related: at Xena on Thursday Andrew Yang and Heather had a long discussion about getting <code>norm_num</code>working  in characteristic <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span></span></span></span> rings.</p>",
        "id": 520221561,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1748112383
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"214703\">Yury G. Kudryashov</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/.60abel.60.20in.20.60AddCircle.201.60/near/520221353\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>If you can move this to a relation on <code>Real</code> (e.g., <code>PMOD</code>), then it should be easy to write a <code>norm_num</code> extension.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>How do we use that to make <code>abel</code> work?</p>",
        "id": 520223615,
        "sender_full_name": "Jovan Gerbscheid",
        "timestamp": 1748113963
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"110038\">Kevin Buzzard</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/.60abel.60.20in.20.60AddCircle.201.60/near/520221561\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Related: at Xena on Thursday Andrew Yang and Heather had a long discussion about getting <code>norm_num</code>working  in characteristic <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span></span></span></span> rings.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Hopefully, the same approach can be used for both characteristic <code>p</code> and for <code>AddCircle n</code> where <code>n</code> is a natural number literal (in e.g. the reals)</p>",
        "id": 520223727,
        "sender_full_name": "Jovan Gerbscheid",
        "timestamp": 1748114056
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Partial progress for char p is at <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/25133\">#25133</a>. The <code>isRat</code> return type of <code>norm_num</code> only supports division rings so this might not apply to <code>AddCircle</code> without some more serious modifications.</p>",
        "id": 520224372,
        "sender_full_name": "Andrew Yang",
        "timestamp": 1748114593
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Can't you replace the <code>norm_num</code> extension by a simproc?</p>",
        "id": 520224461,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1748114656
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>BTW, is this your actual goal, or do you want to normalize this as a part of a larger ring expression?</p>",
        "id": 520225845,
        "sender_full_name": "Yury G. Kudryashov",
        "timestamp": 1748115788
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It is my actual goal: a linear combination (actually in <code>Real.Angle</code>, but I can convert into <code>AddCircle 1</code>) which I want to be solved by <code>abel</code>.</p>",
        "id": 520225973,
        "sender_full_name": "Jovan Gerbscheid",
        "timestamp": 1748115895
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>As Yael wrote above, another option is to write a simproc that simplifies <code>((m / n : Real) : AddCircle 1)</code>.</p>",
        "id": 520226170,
        "sender_full_name": "Yury G. Kudryashov",
        "timestamp": 1748116037
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>... to <code>((m % n / n : Real) : AddCircle 1)</code>.</p>",
        "id": 520226193,
        "sender_full_name": "Yury G. Kudryashov",
        "timestamp": 1748116062
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In fact, you can even have it as a <code>simp</code> lemma (assuming an unused assumption <code>n \\le m</code> to avoid cycles).</p>",
        "id": 520226247,
        "sender_full_name": "Yury G. Kudryashov",
        "timestamp": 1748116088
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Here's a sequence of tactics that I think covers my use case.</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">AddCircle</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℝ</span><span class=\"o\">))</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">↑</span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">/</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℝ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">↑</span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">/</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">9</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℝ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">refine</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">sub_eq_zero</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">mp</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">?_</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">abel_nf</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">simp</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">only</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"bp\">←</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">QuotientAddGroup</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">mk_add</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">←</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">QuotientAddGroup</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">mk_zsmul</span><span class=\"o\">]</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">refine</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">AddCircle</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">coe_eq_zero_iff</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">_</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">mpr</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">?_</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">use</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">?</span><span class=\"n\">n</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">norm_num</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">norm_cast</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">exact</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">rfl</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 520227134,
        "sender_full_name": "Jovan Gerbscheid",
        "timestamp": 1748116879
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I assume that <code>AddCircle 1</code> is being used as a proxy for <code>Real.Angle</code> here, to avoid having to deal with π?</p>",
        "id": 520232428,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1748121833
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Or is it genuinely useful in its own right?</p>",
        "id": 520232477,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1748121846
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Theorems about dynamics on the circle are often stated for <code>AddCircle 1</code> (though some authors use a very useful lemma <code>2\\pi = 1</code> and don't care about it).</p>",
        "id": 520238938,
        "sender_full_name": "Yury G. Kudryashov",
        "timestamp": 1748128594
    }
]